          <l corresp="1">With an appearance that put the the young-rayed (i.e. rising) sun to shame, </l>
          <l corresp="2">a lady with flowing matted locks [and] with a body of shining brightness,</l>
          <l corresp="3">having appeared on the summit of the tall mountain that glitters with/like
            gold (Mēru)</l>
          <l corresp="4">[she] who had departed towards the south, [she who is] the
            deity of this
            island,</l>
          <l corresp="5">having stopped beneath a branching Jaumoon plum tree,</l>
          <l corresp="6">having heard of the sorrow coming to Great Lady Earth,</l>
          <l corresp="7">[she
            who] had done penance as a harsh enemy to/who had endured the harsh emnity of the demons
            of harsh vigour</l>
          <l corresp="8">she who is called 'Campu'('Jaumoon Plum'), the Lady of
            Campāpati ('Town of Jaumoon Plums')–</l>
          <l corresp="14"> when there appeared, having
            mingled with the expanse of foaming water (i.e. the sea)</l>
          <l corresp="13">near to [the
            town of] Campāpati, whither
            she had flowed straight towards
            the east,</l>
          <l corresp="12">the Maiden Kāviri, who had been poured from his pitcher</l>
          <l corresp="11">by the immortal sage Akattiyaṉ,</l>
          <l corresp="10">[Akattiyaṉ] to whom the
            lovely king/King Kānta/[King] Kāntamaṉ had
            sacrificed, with desire for the River Gaṅgā,</l>
          <l corresp="9"> [Gaṅgā] who exalts the
            luminuous/sacred family of the red-rayed lord [the
            Sun].</l>
          <l corresp="15">the ancient female of extreme austerities [Campu], who was
            sweetly seated
            there [in the town of Campāpati],</l>
          <l corresp="16">having gladly/joyfully received the
            maiden of
            spreading/high-rising/flooding
            waters [Kāviri] there</l>
          <l corresp="17">with the words, 'O aetherial Gaṅgā, from the
            affectionate sky!'</l>
          <l corresp="18">Come, o lamp which puts an end to intense desire!'</l>
          <l corresp="19">the man of great penance who doesn't hate (i.e. prefers; or
            preferred) a back position [Akattiyaṉ], having heard [what had
            happened] here, </l>
          <l corresp="20ab"> said [to Kāviri], 'O mother, listen!</l>
          <l corresp="20cd-21">bow down to this ancient lady of extreme austerities [Campu], who is
            worthy to be (lit. who is of a nature to be) bowed
            down to by you!' </l>
          <l corresp="23"> [And so] the creeper/flag of the Cōḻa family of
            the undeviating, straight sceptre</l>
          <l corresp="22">–[the Cōḻa family/the
            sceptre] that has become famous (lit. grown high) in India because of its excellence
            which
            is worthy to be sung–</l>
          <l corresp="25">the cool Tamil maiden (Kāviri), who does
            not change [her] position [i.e. she doesn't dry out], </l>
          <l corresp="24">although,
            because of the planets changing [their] positions, the summers last longer [there]–</l>
          <l corresp="26">stood still as one who worshipped [Campu]. That very ancient lady [Campu], </l>
          <l corresp="27">having sat, taking [Kāviri] [onto her] lap with overflowing joy, </l>
          <l corresp="29">said, 'On that day on which the ancient one of the red flower [Brahmā]
            made </l>
          <l corresp="28"> the embryos of gods and the embryos of Brahmā</l>
          <l corresp="30">this
            ancient city of great name took on my name [Campāpati]. </l>
          <l corresp="31">[Now]
            I have given [it] your name (Kāvirippūmpaṭṭiṉam). May you live [long]!' </l>
          <l corresp="34a-b">(1) The announcement [by drum] of the Great Festival </l>
          <l corresp="32">
            in the beautiful ancient city with a two-part name</l>
          <l corresp="33"> to the strong one
            [Indra] [in the form of] one hundred sacrifices; </l>
          <l corresp="35"> (2) and the saying
            to Mātavi through Vayantamālai </l>
          <l corresp="36"> by Cittirāpati with broken heart </l>
          <l corresp="34cd"> that the gossip had become big; </l>
          <l corresp="37-38"> (3) and the going by Maṇimēkalai inside the flower-grove with its beautiful blossoms in order to
            pluck big blossoms, </l>
          <l corresp="40">(4) and the entering of the Crystal Chamber, after she
            had seen in the area </l>
          <l corresp="39"> the royal young prince there in that flower-grove; </l>
          <l corresp="41"> (5) and that man [the young prince], having seen the girl [Maṇimēkalai]
            who had entered the Crystal Chamber,</l>
          <l corresp="42"> after he had left with grief in his trembling heart; </l>
          <l corresp="43"> the coming and manifesting of Maṇimēkalā Deity; </l>
          <l corresp="44"> (6) and the carrying off of Maṇimēkalai to Maṇipallavam –</l>
          <l corresp="46"> (7) and the rousing of Cutamati from sleep </l>
          <l corresp="45"> in the garden by that deity worthy to be spoken of; </l>
          <l corresp="48"> (8) and the waking from sleep and the suffering of singular/solitary
